{[%evp 0,39,26,0,37,19,5,3,7,39,33,33,29,29,45,32,23,30,32,32,24,27,27,20,39,31,24,23,19,12,-4,-12,0,0,0,0,67,68,50,56,50,55] In this chapter, we will look at the side plans for Black. In general, they do not pretend to be a complete equality, but some knowledge is still required from Whites. The main plans for Black: 1) Qb6 setup; 2) Nh6-f5 setup; 3) "The hedgehog" style- b6.} 1. c4 g6 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 (5... Qb6 $6 {Here it is a dubious idea. It is better to play 5...Nc6 6.Be3 and only now 6...Qb6. We will see it later.} 6. Nb5 $1 {Strong} (6. Nb3 {It's also a possible move, but less principal. In the following games, Black solves all the problems.} Qc7 7. Be2 d6 8. O-O Nc6 9. Re1 $5 {We want to avoid Bc3 idea.} (9. Na3 a6 10. Nc2 Nf6 11. f3 Nd7 12. Rb1 Nce5 13. Ne3 Nb6 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 O-O {0-1 (42) Abdurakhmanov,M (2284)-Vakhidov,J (2533) Tashkent 2021}) (9. f4 a6 10. Kh1 Be6 11. Qd2 a5 (11... b5 $5 $13 {was even stronger}) 12. a4 Qb6 13. Ra3 Nf6 14. Nc3 O-O $132 {1-0 (46) Brunello,S (2725)-Vakhidov,J (2530) Almaty 2022}) (9. Nc3 $6 Bxc3 $1 {Very important idea for Black. After this White has a long-term problem with the pawn structure.} 10. bxc3 Nf6 $132) 9... Nf6 10. Nc3 $14 {White is better}) 6... a6 (6... Nc6 $2 7. c5 $1 Qxc5 8. Nc7+ Kd8 9. Nxa8 $18) (6... Qd8 7. N1c3 a6 8. Nd4 Nc6 9. Be3 Nf6 10. Be2 $16 {а6 useless move}) 7. Be3 Qd8 {He should return his Queen.} 8. Nd4 Nf6 9. Nc3 $16 {White made all useful moves. Black spent time on a 6 move, but it was not a part of his plane. White has a normal position with an extra tempo(a6).}) 6. Be3 {This is the starting position of this chapter.} Qb6 {Another Black's try with the same idea to capture White's knight on c3 in the future. These positions are played very well by the grandmaster J.Vakhidov from Uzbekistan. I recommend watching his games for those who want to play these positions with Black.} (6... d6 7. Nc3 Qb6 $5 {With the idea of spoiling the pawns after Nb3 Bc3.} ({we saw} 7... Nh6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O {ctrl+f7}) (7... Nf6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 {it is a main line. We will look it later.}) (7... Nxd4 8. Bxd4 Nf6 {it is a main line. We will look it later.} (8... Bxd4 $6 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. Rad1 a5 13. f4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] with an attack} Nc5 14. e5 $18)) 8. Ndb5 $1 {Important. White should sacrifice on b2.} (8. Ncb5 $6 {is worse} Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Nf6 {this endgame is OK for Black} 12. f3 O-O 13. Be2 Nd7 14. Kf2 a5 $11 {1/2 (26) Nagy,G (2433)-Vorobiov,E (2585) Schwaebisch Gmuend 2017}) (8. Nd5 $6 {only a draw} Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qxa2 10. Ra1 Qb2 11. Rb1 Qa2 12. Ra1 {1/2 (12) Puranik,A (2479)-Vorobiov,E (2585) Pardubice 2017}) (8. Nb3 $6 {allows} Bxc3+ $1 9. bxc3 Qc7 $13 {White has weak pawns, and it is very difficult to use Black squares, because the position remains closed. In the following examples, Black has convincingly solved his opening problems} 10. c5 (10. Bd3 Nf6 11. O-O b6 12. h3 Ne5 13. Bh6 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nd7 $15 (14... Ba6 15. Nd2 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gd7e5,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] 1-0 (34) Alekseev,E (2636)-Savchenko,B (2613) Sochi 2016})) (10. Be2 Nf6 11. f3 O-O 12. O-O b6 13. a4 Ba6 (13... Ne5 14. a5 Be6 15. f4 Nxc4 16. Bd4 Nxe4 $19 17. Qe1 d5 18. Bxc4 Qxc4 19. Nd2 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 Bf5 {1/2 (58) Sonis,F (2425)-Papp,G (2607) Caleta 2018}) 14. Nd4 Na5 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. cxb5 $15) (10. h4 Nf6 11. Be2 h5 12. O-O Nxe4 13. Bf3 Nf6 14. c5 dxc5 15. Nxc5 O-O 16. Re1 Rd8 17. Qa4 Ne5 18. Be2 Neg4 $19 {1-0 (52) Lintchevski,D (2555)-Ivic,V (2581) chess.com INT 2021}) (10. f4 Nf6 11. Bd3 Na5 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4]} 12. O-O Nxc4 13. Bd4 O-O $132 {White has to prove a compensation}) 10... dxc5 11. Nxc5 (11. Bxc5 Nf6 12. f3 O-O 13. Be2 Be6 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Qc2 b6 16. Bf2 Ne5 17. c4 Nh5 18. Rfc1 Nf4 $15 {1/2 (47) Bryzgalin,K (2424)-Vorobiov,E (2585) Pardubice 2017}) 11... Nf6 12. f3 O-O 13. Be2 b6 14. Nb3 Nh5 15. Qc1 Ne5 16. O-O Nc4 17. Bh6 Rd8 18. Rd1 Ba6 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $132 {Black is fine 1-0 (53) Kokarev,D (2608)-Savchenko,B (2566) Vladivostok 2015}) 8... Bxc3+ (8... Qa5 {just bad} 9. Bd2 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Qd8 (9... Rb8 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Bc3 Bxc3+ 12. Nbxc3 $16) 10. Nd5 Kf8 11. Nbc3 $16 {[%csl Rf8] White stabilized the situation and gained a huge advantage.}) 9. Nxc3 (9. Ke2 $6 {is not enough} Nd4+ 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Nf6 {Black confidently equalized the game. Then, using a typical f5 idea, Black seized the initiative and won.} 13. f3 e5 14. Nb5 Ke7 15. Kd2 a6 16. Nc3 Be6 17. Be2 Nd7 18. g3 f5 19. exf5 gxf5 20. b3 Nf6 $132 {0-1 (55) Maghsoodloo,P (2685)-Vorobiov,E (2557) St Petersburg 2018}) 9... Qxb2 {Now White has a choise.} 10. Nb5 (10. Nd5 {is a good try} Nb4 (10... Kf8 $6 11. Be2 Qe5 12. f3 h5 13. O-O h4 14. Qd2 $18 {wins} b6 15. f4 Qg7 16. e5 Be6 17. exd6 Rd8 18. dxe7+ Ngxe7 19. Rad1 Bxd5 20. Bf3 Nf5 21. cxd5 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 Ne7 {1-0 (62) Le,Q (2713)-Savchenko,B (2577) Moscow 2019}) 11. Rc1 $1 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nf6 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Bf5 (14... Qxa2 $2 15. Ra1 Qb2 16. Bd4 Qb4 17. Ra4 $18 {[%csl Rb4] and Queen is trapped.}) 15. Bd4 Qb4 16. Re1 $16 {It is a terrible position for Black.}) 10... Kf8 (10... Nb4 $2 11. Rc1 $18 Nf6 12. Bd4 Qxa2 13. Nc7+ $18 {[%cal Gc7a8]}) (10... Nf6 $2 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Rb1 Qc3+ 13. Bd2 Qa3 14. Nxa8 {wins} Nxe4 15. Bd3 Nc5 16. Be2 Bf5 17. Rb5 Kd7 18. O-O $18) 11. Be2 Nf6 (11... Qg7 {here Black didn't finish a development} 12. O-O b6 13. e5 Nxe5 14. Nxd6 Be6 15. f4 Rd8 16. Nf5 Rxd1 17. Raxd1 Nc6 18. Nxg7 Kxg7 19. Bf3 $18 {1-0 (28) Karjakin,S (2753)-Savchenko,B (2562) St Petersburg 2018}) (11... Qb4+ 12. Bd2 Qc5 13. O-O Nf6 14. Bh6+ Kg8 15. Nc7 Rb8 16. Nd5 $18) 12. Bh6+ Kg8 13. O-O Qe5 14. Nc7 Rb8 15. Nd5 $16 {White will prepare a break in the center and win.}) 7. Nb3 $1 {is stronger} (7. Nb5 Qa5+ 8. N1c3 (8. Bd2 $6 Qd8 9. Bc3 Nf6 {[%csl Gb5] White'sWhite's knight is out of play. Black is fine.} 10. Nd2 O-O 11. Be2 a6 12. Nd4 d6 13. O-O Bd7 14. N4b3 Qb8 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5] 0-1 (38) Tutisani,N (2460)-Guseinov,G (2654) Nakhchivan 2018}) 8... Nf6 9. f3 O-O 10. Be2 a6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 d6 13. O-O Be6 14. b3 Rac8 {A typical situation for this opening. After trading on d4, Black has a slightly worse, but very solid position.}) 7... Qd8 {offering a draw} (7... Qb4+ 8. Bd2 Qb6 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Be3 Qd8 13. f3 $14 {is fine for White}) (7... Qc7 {waiting for Nc3} 8. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2b2,Gb1c3]} (8. Nc3 $6 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nf6 $132) 8... Nf6 9. Nc3 $5 {the strongest move} (9. f3 {White defends from Ng4 jump.} O-O 10. Nc3 d6 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Be2 Nd7 {0-1 (44) Horvath,D (2542)-Bjerre,J (2642) New York 2024} 13. O-O {White is better. Queen on c7 can be easily attacked.} a5 14. Nb5 Qd8 15. N3d4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 a4 17. f4 $14 {White is preparing a typical attacking plan on the kingside. The e6 bishop is always in danger, because of the f5 threat.}) 9... O-O ({Now} 9... Ng4 $2 {is bad} 10. Bf4 d6 (10... Qd8 11. c5 O-O 12. Be2 $18) (10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 $18 {[%csl Yh8]}) 11. c5 $1 Nge5 12. Nb5 Qd7 13. cxd6 $18 {wins}) 10. Be2 d6 11. O-O $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc3d5] compared to the f3 variation, White has an extra tempo.}) 8. Qd2 $1 (8. Nc3 $6 {is bad} Bxc3+ $1 9. bxc3 Nf6 10. f3 d6 $132 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4][%cal Gc8e6,Gc6e5,Gd8c7] We discussed this idea earlier, and Black is also fine here.}) 8... Nf6 (8... d6 9. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Yf6g4]} 10. Be2 O-O (10... Ng4 11. Bxg4 Bxg4 12. Nd4 $1 {an important move} (12. O-O Ne5 $1 $15 {[%csl Yc4]}) 12... O-O 13. O-O Qa5 14. Rab1 Rac8 15. b3 Bd7 16. Rfd1 $14 {White is better. His light squared bishop is not really important in this pawn structure.}) 11. O-O a5 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bd7 14. b3 Bc6 15. f3 Nd7 {It is a transposition to a main line. We will discuss it in another chapter}) 9. f3 {avoiding Ng4} (9. Nc3 Ng4 {usually Black is happy to make this move} 10. Bf4 d6 11. h3 Nf6 12. Be2 {a calm alternative, slightly better for White.} (12. Bh6 $5 {An interesting plan with a castling to the queenside. White is planning an attack on the kingside. Objectively, White is a bit better, but Black has a decent counterplay.} O-O 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. O-O-O (14. f4 a5 15. Be2 a4 16. Nd4 {1-0 (63) Niemann,H (2708)-Vakhidov,J (2607) Sharjah 2023} Qb6 $132) 14... Be6 (14... Qb6 15. g4 Be6 16. f4 a5 17. f5 a4 18. Na1 Bd7 19. Nc2 Qc5 20. Be2 Ne5 {0-1 (61) Sethuraman,S (2643)-Vakhidov,J (2607) Jerusalem 2022}) 15. f4 a5 16. g4 a4 17. Nd4 Qb6 18. Nc2 Na5 19. Ne3 a3 $132) 12... O-O 13. O-O Be6 14. Rad1 Nd7 15. Be3 Rc8 16. Bh6 ({In the next game, Black showed a typical counterplay.} 16. f4 Na5 $1 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Nd5 Qxd2 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Bxd2 Rce8 {0-1 (71) Repka,C (2516)-Vakhidov,J (2564) Chennai 2022} 21. f5 Rxe7 22. fxe6 Nc5 23. Rxf7 Rexf7 24. exf7 Bd4+ 25. Kh1 Bxb2 $13) 16... Nce5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nd5 Nf6 19. Qd4 $14 {keeping the pressure.}) 9... O-O (9... a5 $6 {a typical plan, but it is a bad idea here.} 10. Nc5 $5 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gc5a4,Ga4b6]} a4 11. Nc3 a3 12. b3 Qa5 (12... d6 13. N5a4 Nd7 14. Rd1 O-O 15. Be2 Qa5 16. Nd5 Qxd2+ 17. Bxd2 $16) 13. N5a4 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Ga4b6,Gb6a8,Gb6c8,Ge3b6]} (13. Rc1 d6 14. Nd3 O-O 15. Be2 Be6 16. O-O Nd7 17. Rfd1 $16) 13... d6 14. Rd1 Be6 (14... O-O 15. Nb5 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 $14) 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Be2 Qxd2+ 17. Rxd2 $16 {with better endgame}) 10. Nc3 d6 (10... b6 11. Nd4 Bb7 12. Be2 Rc8 13. O-O Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qc7 15. Rfd1 d6 16. Rac1 $16 {"The hedgehog" setup. It is a typical worse position for Black.}) 11. Be2 (11. O-O-O {An interesting attacking plan. Objectively, Black is absolutely fine here.} Be6 12. Kb1 a6 13. Nd5 b5 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 bxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxd5 17. exd5 Qc8 $132) 11... Be6 (11... Bd7 {was good to play with the idea to capture the White knight on d4 and play Bc6 then. But with the knight on b3, this idea is worse.} 12. O-O $16 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gc3d5]}) 12. O-O Nd7 {[%csl Yb2,Yc4][%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gd8a5,Gc6a5,Rf3f4,Rf4f5] Black's idea is to take the space on the queenside after a5-a4, then he wants to create a counterplay against the b2 and c4 pawns. We'll look at the different arrangements for White. The main plan is to prepare f4-f5 and start an attack on the kingside.} (12... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gd8a5]} 13. Nd4 Nxd4 (13... a4 14. Ndb5 Qa5 15. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) 14. Bxd4 Nd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5] preparing f5}) 13. f4 $5 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gf4f5] now the bishop is under attack} (13. Rad1 {is a good developing move} a5 14. f4 a4 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 {[%cal Gf4f5]} f6 18. Kh1 Qb6 19. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) (13. Rac1 a5 14. Na1 (14. Na4 $6 {the idea is to block a5 pawn, but Black is in time with his counterplay.} Nb4 15. a3 $2 Na2 $1 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Ge6b3]} 16. Ra1 b5 $1 $17) 14... a4 15. Nc2 Qa5 16. Na3 Nb6 17. Rfd1 Qb4 18. Nd5 Qxd2 19. Rxd2 Nd7 20. Nb5 $14 {White was slightly better 1-0 (82) Ponkratov,P (2629)-Vakhidov,J (2534) Krasnaya Polyana 2021}) (13. Rfd1 a5 $5 14. Na4 Nce5 $1 15. Rac1 Nxc4 16. Rxc4 {and now Black got a counterplay} b5 $1 {1/2 (41) Pantsulaia,L (2564)-Vakhidov,J (2534) Krasnaya Polyana 2021} 17. Rcc1 bxa4 18. Nd4 Nc5 $132) 13... Nc5 {is the best} (13... Na5 14. Nxa5 Qxa5 15. Rac1 Rfc8 (15... Bxc3 16. Rxc3 $16) 16. b3 Nc5 17. Bf3 Bd7 18. Rfd1 $14 {White is better}) (13... Nb6 $2 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 14. Nd5 $1 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7] Black's pawns are weak}) 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6g1,Gb6b2] with an idea to trade White queen} (15... Bxd4+ $2 {is bad} 16. Qxd4 {[%cal Yb2b4]} a5 17. Rad1 Bd7 18. e5 $16) 16. Rad1 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 f6 $1 {Now White is a bit better after} (17... Qxb2 $2 {is too dangerous} 18. f5 Bd7 19. Rb1 Qa3 20. Rf3 f6 21. fxg6 Ne6 (21... hxg6 22. Nd5 $16) 22. gxh7+ Kh8 23. Qf2 $16 {[%cal Yf3g3,Yc3d5,Ye2h5] with an attack}) 18. Rd2 $5 {Here, White is ready to play a slightly better endgame.} ({or} 18. b3 a5 19. Rfe1 a4 {1/2 (45) Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Vakhidov,J (2534) Krasnaya Polyana 2021} 20. Nb5 axb3 21. axb3 Bf7 22. e5 $5 dxe5 23. fxe5 fxe5 24. Qe3 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Ge7][%cal Ge2f3] but here Black is very close to equality/=.}) 18... Nd7 (18... a5 19. Rfd1 Nd7 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. b3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Ge2f3,Ge4e5] White can play it without any risk}) 19. Qxb6 Nxb6 20. b3 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3,Ye4e5,Rh2h5,Yc4c5] We got this endgame. White is a bit better, but Black's position is very solid. White should slowly improve his pieces and prepare breaks in the center(e5 or c5) or on the kingside after h4-h5. The good news for White is that it's a very safe position, and only White can play it for an advantage. In conclusion, I want to say that in the considered variants, Black does not claim to equalise completely.} *

