{[%evp 0,39,26,0,37,19,5,3,7,39,33,33,29,29,45,32,23,30,32,32,24,27,27,20,39,31,24,23,19,12,-4,-12,0,0,0,0,67,68,50,56,50,55] In this chapter, we will look at the side plans for Black. In general, they do not pretend to be a complete equality, but some knowledge is still required from Whites. The main plans for Black: 1) Qb6 setup; 2) Nh6-f5 setup; 3) "The hedgehog" style- b6.} 1. c4 g6 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Be3 {This is the starting position of this chapter.} b6 $6 {"The hedgehog" plan. Here, Black's position is worse than that of a normal "hedgehog" because Black's knight is on c6, and Black doesn't have typical counterplay. White can trade dark squared bishops after Qd2 and Bh6. White khight will be really strong on d5. If Black wants to chase him away after e6, their d6 pawn will be weaken.} (6... Nh6 $6 {[%cal Gf7f5] Preparing f5 shortly. Unfortunately for Black, this plan leads to pawn weaknesses, but does not provide sufficient compensation for it.} 7. Nc3 (7. h3 f5 8. exf5 Nxf5 9. Nxf5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Qxf5 11. Qd2 d6 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Be6 14. Rac1 Qa5 15. b3 $16 {with very pleasant position 1-0 (30) Roiz,M (2594)-Shukh,N (2435) Minsk 2015}) 7... O-O 8. Be2 d6 (8... f5 $6 {too early} 9. exf5 Bxd4 (9... Nxf5 10. Nxf5 Rxf5 11. O-O {calm development} (11. h4 {Interesting plan for White.} d6 12. g4 Rf8 13. h5 $16 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ge1c1]}) 11... Bxc3 $5 {after f5 this plan is insufficient for equality.} (11... d6 12. Qd2 $16) 12. bxc3 b6 13. Re1 e6 (13... Bb7 14. Bg4) 14. c5 $1 {White wants to open the center for his bishops.} Qc7 (14... bxc5 15. Qd6 Qf6 16. Rad1 Qe5 17. Bg4 Rf7 18. Bf3 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 $16 {[%csl Ge3,Gf3][%cal Ge3c5]}) 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Qb3 $16) 10. Bxh6 Rxf5 11. O-O d6 (11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 d6 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. Bf3 $16) 12. Qd2 Qa5 13. Be3 Qe5 (13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Be6 15. Rab1 $16 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb1b5]}) 14. Bxd4 Qxd4 15. Rad1 Qxd2 16. Rxd2 {and White got better endgame} Be6 17. f4 Raf8 18. g3 Bc8 19. b3 Kg7 20. Bf3 $16 {1-0 (33) Wen,Y (2608)-Gholami,A (2489) Moscow 2018}) 9. O-O (9. Qd2 $6 {Allows for unnecessary simplifications} Ng4 10. Bxg4 Bxg4 11. O-O Rc8 12. b3 a6 13. Rac1 Bd7 {1/2 (51) Lupulescu,C (2525)-Gavrilescu,D (2274) Bucharest 2019}) 9... f5 {the point of Nh6 line} (9... Bd7 10. Qd2 Ng4 11. Bxg4 Bxg4 {Now the bishop gets to g4 in two tempos.} 12. b3 Qa5 13. h3 Bd7 14. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5]}) 10. exf5 Nxf5 11. Nxf5 Bxf5 12. Qd2 Qd7 (12... Qa5 {It does not change the evaluation, White is better after a simple development in the center.} 13. Rac1 Rad8 14. Rfe1 $16) 13. Rad1 Rad8 14. h3 Qe8 15. Rfe1 Qf7 16. b3 $16 {We can summarize this plan: Black created weaknesses in the center and did not get any counterplay. White has a very pleasant game.}) 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Be2 Nf6 9. O-O d6 10. f3 O-O 11. Nc2 $5 {avoiding Nd4} (11. Qd2 {is the main move, White is also better here.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b4 a5 15. a3 $14) 11... Rc8 (11... e6 $5 {An interesting try. Black wants to play d5. It is a very typical idea for "The Hedgehog".} 12. Qe1 $5 (12. Qd2 $6 d5 $1 {after this break in the center Black is fine} 13. exd5 exd5 14. Rad1 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Qe7 $11) 12... Rc8 ({now} 12... d5 $6 {is worse} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gc3d5] and Nd5}) 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. b3 $14 {[%cal Ge1h4,Ge3g5,Gg5h6]}) 12. Qd2 Nd7 13. Bh6 a5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rad1 $16 {is better for White. We can prepare Nd5 and then f4-f5.} *

