{[%evp 0,35,19,38,72,49,116,112,59,74,84,16,34,24,22,23,25,5,22,20,18,4,58,55,55,10,2,1,35,22,54,6,51,68,90,44,31,81] In this chapter, we will explore Black's plan to capture the space on the kingside. Black often puts his pawns on d6 and b6 and then plays g5-h5-h4. At the same time, Black has a positional idea to fix the White pawns on the White squares and use this in the endgame. Another idea is to try to create an attack on the kingside. Most often, White plans to break through on the queenside. At the same time, it is advisable for White to prevent the exchange of pieces. Currently, this arrangement is considered suspicious for Blacks. To understand the ideas, we will analyze several classic games, and then I will show how White gets an advantage.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. c4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 Ne6 $5 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gb7b6,Gd7d6,Gg6g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4,Gc8b7,Ge6f4] [#] Most often, in this variant, Black implements the specified plan. The knight's position on e6 is very flexible, as it can support the movement of Black pawns on the kingside and prevent the movement of White pawns on the queenside. It is advantageous for Black to exchange queens and dark-square bishops. To do this, they are ready to double pawns. We will see it in Gelfand-Jobava.} 10. Rc1 (10. Qd2 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5c3,Gg7c3]} 11. Rc1 $5 {protects the knight} (11. Be2 $6 {is bad} Bxc3 $1 12. bxc3 b6 $13 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4] Black gets strong counterplay against White pawns}) 11... b6 12. Be2 Bb7 13. f3 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gh7h5] Black finished his development. Now it is time to push kingside pawns.} g5 ({In this game we will see a good example of Black playing this structure.} 13... h5 14. b3 h4 {grabs more space [#]} 15. Nd5 $6 {works great for Black. As we know, Black is happy to trade queens.} ({White should keep more pieces on the board} 15. O-O $1 d6 16. Rfd1 g5 $14 {[%cal Gg7e5,Ge5f4]}) 15... Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bh6 $5 {Another great trade. Black fixed White pawns on light squares, so exchanging the defender of dark squares is a good idea.} 17. Rhd1 Bxe3+ 18. Kxe3 g5 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Ge4,Gf3,Gg2] is not a great situation for White bishop because it is very passive now.} 19. b4 d6 20. c5 $5 {White has made a typical breakthrough on the queenside, but this is not enough for an advantage here} bxc5 21. bxc5 dxc5 22. Nc3 Bc6 23. Bc4 Nd4 $11 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black was fine in Kramnik,V (2710)-Ljubojevic,L (2600) Monte Carlo 1994}) 14. O-O Be5 15. Rfd1 d6 (15... Rd8 16. a3 Bf4 $5 {another way to trade bishops} 17. Bxf4 gxf4 {[%csl Gf4,Gf7][%cal Gg8g2]} 18. Nd5 $6 {once again, White should avoid any tradings} (18. b4 Qg5 19. Bf1 $16 {[%cal Ga3a4,Ga4a5] and White is better}) 18... Qxd2 19. Rxd2 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3] and Black got a counterplay 1/2 (49) Sjugirov, S (2664) -Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2625) Abu Dhabi 2015}) 16. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga3a4,Ga4a5] White prepares b4-a4-a5.} Bf4 17. Bxf4 gxf4 {[%csl Gf4,Gf7][%cal Gg8g2,Ga5g5] In this structure, Black is looking for an active play on the kingside} 18. b4 Qg5 (18... Qxa3 $2 19. Nd5 $18 {[%csl Ge8]}) 19. Nd5 Rg8 20. Bf1 Kf8 {White has defended his king, but how can he improve his position further?[#]} 21. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga7,Gb6][%cal Ga4a5] A typical plan. White creates weaknesses for Black on the queenside!} h5 22. a5 h4 23. axb6 axb6 24. Nxb6 $18 {White won a pawn, position is hopeless for Black. 1-0 (37) Kortschnoj,V-Nei,I Leningrad 1962}) 10... Qa5 {This is the idea of this line. Otherwise, Black just gets a bad position.} (10... b6 {is a bad version of Hedgehog for Black.} 11. g3 $5 Bb7 12. Bg2 Qc8 13. Qe2 O-O 14. O-O d6 15. Rfd1 $16 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gb2b4] 1-0 (55) Adams,J (2336)-Edwards,K (2216) ICCF email 2017}) (10... O-O {is a bad version of Hedgehog for Black.} 11. Be2 d6 12. O-O b6 13. b4 Bb7 14. Qd3 Nc7 15. Rfd1 Qd7 16. h3 Rfc8 17. Bg4 e6 18. Bf4 h5 19. Be2 e5 20. Be3 $16 {1-0 (74) Maierhofer, J (2290)-Stanojevic,S (2392) ICCF email 2018}) 11. Be2 ({In this game, we will see an interesting attack plan for Black on the kingside. Whites should avoid such complications.} 11. a3 b6 12. Bd3 g5 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rc2 Bxc3 15. Rxc3 Qe5 16. Re1 h5 17. Bd2 Rh6 {[#]} 18. h4 $6 {too optimistic} (18. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Yc4c5,Ya3a5] was better}) 18... Rg6 19. hxg5 Nxg5 20. Qxh5 Qg7 $44 {[%cal Gg7g2]} 21. Kf1 Ne6 22. g3 O-O-O $17 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gd8h8] White has an extra pawn, but the king's position is very dangerous. 1-0 (30) Leko,P (2635)-Piket,J (2630) Tilburg 1997}) 11... b6 (11... Bxc3+ $6 {is a principal move, but White has a winning position here.} 12. Rxc3 Qxa2 13. f4 (13. Qc1 $44 {[%cal Gf2f5]}) 13... Qxb2 14. Rb3 Qa2 15. O-O $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf4f5] Black's king gonna be trapped very soon.}) ({In the next game, Black abandoned the typical arrangement and lost quickly.} 11... O-O 12. O-O f5 $6 {Black just made new weaknesses in the center} 13. exf5 $18 gxf5 14. f4 Kh8 15. Nd5 {and White gained a decisive advantage in the center.} Qd8 16. b4 b6 17. Rf3 Bb7 18. Rh3 {[%csl Gh8]} Rg8 19. Bd3 Qf8 20. Qh5 h6 21. Qg6 Bxd5 22. Bxf5 Qxf5 23. Qxf5 Bc6 24. Qg6 {1-0 (24) Spassky,B-Espinoza,A Tel Aviv 1964}) 12. O-O (12. Qd5 $5 {is an interesting try [#]} Rb8 $5 ({after} 12... Qxd5 13. cxd5 {[%cal Gc1c7] White wants to play on the queenside}) 13. Qxa5 bxa5 {[%csl Ga5,Ga7][%cal Gb8b2] Another interesting pawn structure. Black is ready to double his pawns but has pressure over the "b" file.} 14. b3 Bd4 $1 {a usual trade of bishops} 15. Bd2 (15. Bxd4 Nxd4 16. Nb5 Nxe2 17. Kxe2 Bb7 18. Ke3 a6 19. Nc7+ Kd8 20. Nd5 Bc6 21. Rb1 Bxd5 22. cxd5 Kc7 23. Rhc1+ Kd6 {1/2 (60) Kitson,K (2282)-Cook,D (2261) ICCF email 2016}) 15... d6 16. O-O Bc5 17. Na4 Ba3 18. Rb1 Bb7 19. f3 Bc6 $132 {and Black is ok here} 20. Bxa5 Bxa4 21. bxa4 Kd7 22. Rfd1 Nc5 $44 {1-0 (113) Gelfand,B (2729)-Jobava,B (2651) Dortmund 2006}) 12... Bb7 13. f3 g5 14. Rf2 $5 {[%cal Ge2f1,Ga2a3,Gb2b4] is an interesting plan. Here, the rook reliably strengthens the second row, the bishop goes to f1, and then the White gradually prepares to move the pawns on the queenside.} ({In this game we will see a good example of Black playing this structure.} 14. a3 Qe5 15. Qd2 h5 16. Rfd1 d6 17. b4 h4 18. Nd5 Kf8 19. Bf1 Bc6 20. Qd3 Nf4 $5 {looking for tradings [#]} 21. Nxf4 $2 {the wrong plan. As we remember, White should keep more pieces on the board.} (21. Qd2 $1 $14 {was better}) 21... gxf4 22. Bd4 Qxd4+ 23. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 24. Rxd4 {[%csl Gf4,Gh4] White has a very passive bishop. Black's pawn structure is better, because it is very hard to attack his pawns. How to play?[#]} Rh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5a5] strong improving move} 25. c5 $5 {an active try} dxc5 26. bxc5 b5 27. e5 h3 $1 28. Re1 hxg2 29. Bxg2 {[%csl Ga3,Gc5,Ge5,Gf3,Gh2] all White pawns are weak} Rc8 30. Rxf4 Bd5 31. e6 f6 $17 {and Black won it slowly 0-1 (74) Short,N (2615)-Larsen,B (2565) Brussels 1987}) 14... h5 15. Bf1 Qe5 (15... Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Bc6 17. c5 b5 18. Ra3 Qc7 19. Qd2 Rg8 20. b4 $14 {1-0 (62) Parushev,A (2294)-Stefanov,P (2286) ICCF email 2016}) 16. Rd2 d6 17. Nd5 Kf8 18. b4 $16 {[%cal Ya2a5,Yc4c5] White is better 1/2 (42) Short,N (2620)-Larsen,B (2570) Hastings 1987. Conclusion: Even though Black is objectively in a worse position, this system deserves attention. Interesting pawn structures are possible here, which require a deep understanding on both sides.} *

