{[%evp 0,37,19,31,72,53,100,79,79,84,50,28,23,25,24,34,18,6,22,12,29,32,34,33,28,3,3,-7,11,0,-8,16,26,42,26,21,22,16,6,-26] In this chapter, we will analyze the pawn structure, that occurs after the Black pawn moves to e5. Black captures the space in the center. The d4 square is White's weakness. That's where Black puts his knight. Black can attack the c4 pawn by a6-b5 and the e4 pawn by f5. On the other hand, Black creates a weak pawn on d6. White most often plays these positions in the center by exchanging a strong Black knight d4 and then attacking the d6 pawn or on the queenside by capturing the space after a4-a5-b4-c5. White also has an interesting plan of attack on the kingside. To do this, White makes 0-0-0 and then plays h4-h5 with an attack along the "h" line. This plan is not the most reliable for White, but it leads to an interesting fight. This pawn structure is quite reliable for Black, but White can play these positions without much risk if desired.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. c4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Rd7][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Yf7f5,Gd2d7,Ya2a4,Ya4a5,Yb2b4,Rh2h5] Most often, in this variant, Black implements the specified plan. Black has a great knight on d4, but a retarded "d" pawn.} 10. Bd3 {for White, the best thing is to place all the pieces in the center.} ({immediate} 10. Nb5 {is not dangerous at all} d6 $1 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Qa5+ 13. Ke2 Be5 $1 $44 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gc8e6] Black is fine 1/2 (31) Andersen,M (2589)-Demuth,A (2538) Germany 2018}) ({White has an interesting attacking plan. He wants to open the "h" file and attack the kingside. White usually moves his king to the queenside.} 10. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ge1c1]} h5 ({The following line shows, what will happen if Black does not respond to White's plan.} 10... h6 11. Qd2 {[%cal Ye1c1]} d6 12. Ne2 $5 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2d6] After d6 White can change his plan. It is a good idea to trade strong Black knight.} Nc6 13. O-O-O Be6 14. Qxd6 Qa5 (14... Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Bxc4 16. Nc3 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 Nd4 18. h5 Ke7 19. Rd5 $16 {White is better}) 15. Nc3 Rd8 16. Qc5 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Qxc5 18. Bxc5 $16 {in this endgame, Black does not have enough compensation for a pawn.}) 11. Nd5 d6 (11... O-O 12. g4 $1 hxg4 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Qxg4 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ge1c1] an ideal situation for White}) 12. Bg5 f6 {White provokes new weaknesses.} (12... Qa5+ $4 13. b4 $18) 13. Be3 O-O 14. Bd3 f5 15. Bg5 Qe8 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. O-O $14 {[%csl Rd6,Re5,Rg6] Black is not in danger of attacking the king, but he has many weaknesses in the center.}) 10... d6 11. O-O O-O {This is the starting position of this variation, White can try different plans here.} 12. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gb2b4] an interesting plan for capturing space on the queenside. Black tried different answers here.} ({The normal plan is} 12. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gb2b3,Yb7b5,Yf7f5] First of all, White wants to put all the pieces in the center. Black completes the development and prepares b5 or f5.} Be6 ({is another interesting way to develop the bishop} 12... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Bb1 Rc8 15. b3 Qd7 {White is objectively better, but he made an unsuccessful exchange in the game, after which Black equalized with a good play on the queenside.} 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Ne2 b5 $1 {typical} 18. cxb5 Qxb5 19. Nxd4 {1/2 (33) Liang,A (2589)-Lagarde,M (2616) Stockholm 2019} Qc5 $44 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gf8e8] after this move Black has a good compensation}) 13. b3 ({Using the example of the next game, let's see how White should react to the play with b5.} 13. Rfd1 a6 14. b3 Rc8 15. f3 Qd7 16. Rac1 Rc6 17. Ne2 Rfc8 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. Bf2 Qc7 20. f4 b5 21. f5 Bd7 22. Qb2 Qb6 {The critical moment of the game. White made a trade in the center and seized the space on the kingside. Whites is a bit better. He solved the pawn structure problem incorrectly in the game and lost his advantage.} 23. cxb5 $6 ({it was better to improve the queen} 23. Qe2 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3] , because Black doesn't have any counterplay after} bxc4 24. Bxc4 $16) 23... Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 25. Qxc1 axb5 $11 {0-1 (40) Vera Siguenas,D (2528)-Martinez Duany,L (2511) Santa Maria del Mar 2017}) ({White has a long-term advantage, so he doesn't have to rush.} 13. f4 $6 exf4 14. Bxf4 Qa5 $1 15. Bxd6 Rfd8 $44 {and Black has a good compensation}) ({In the next game, Black made a typical counterplay and equalized completely} 13. Ne2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bf4 f5 $5 16. exf5 $6 (16. Rfe1 {was better} fxe4 17. Bxe4 Qd7 18. Rac1 $14 {White is a bit better}) 16... Bxf5 17. Bg3 Rc8 $13 {and Black is fine} 18. Rac1 Qd7 19. b3 d5 $11 20. c5 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Qb5 22. Rfd1 Rfe8 23. Qxb5 axb5 24. Kf1 Rc6 25. Rc2 Rec8 26. Rdc1 Bh6 27. Rd1 Bg7 28. Rdc1 Bh6 29. Rd1 {1/2 (29) Donchenko,A (2636)-Plat,V (2546) Slovakia 2022}) ({In the next game, Black took full control of the dark squares on the queenside} 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Ne2 Qb6 15. b3 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] fixing White pawns on light squares, White bishop can be passive} 16. a4 Rae8 17. Qc2 Qb4 {[%csl Gd3]} 18. Rae1 Bd7 19. Qd1 Bc6 $11 {with good position 1-0 Navara,D (2719)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2536) Ustron 2006}) 13... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. Rad1 Qa5 {Here White can trade queens and play this structure in the endgame.} ({An interesting pawn structure appeared in the following game} 14... Qd7 15. Kh1 ({After} 15. Ne2 {[%cal Gd1d6]} b5 $5 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 bxc4 19. Bxc4 Bxc4 20. bxc4 Qa7 {[%csl Rc4,Gd4,Gd6,Re4][%cal Yf8c8,Ya8b8] the following interesting structure is possible. It looks bad for Black because of the weaknesses of the d pawns, but Black has a counterplay on the open lines.}) 15... b5 {usual counterplay} 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5][%cal Gc1c8,Yf7f5] This structure often arises from the King's Indian defense, usually White has better space and play along the ''c'' line. Black also has weaknesses on the queenside. However, in this position, Black could trade a couple of minor pieces, and his position was not so bad. In the game, Black started a typical counterplay for the King's Indian defense[#]} (17. exd5 {such structure is not dangerous, Black can attack c4 pawn} bxc4 18. bxc4 Rfc8 $13 {[%csl Gc4]}) 17... f5 $5 18. Bxd4 fxe4 $1 (18... exd4 19. exf5 gxf5 20. Rfe1 $16 {is highly unpleasant.}) 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Bxe4 $44 {Black got a compensation for a pawn: 1/2 (50) Bruzon Batista,L (2673)-Edouard,R (2612) Saint Louis 2018}) 15. Nd5 $5 Qxd2 16. Bxd2 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {[%cal Gc1c8,Gf7f5] White wants to use "c" file for his rooks. Black is looking for f5 counterplay.} f5 18. f3 Rac8 19. Rc1 $14 {is better for White, but Black can hold it.}) (12. Ne2 {doesn't help White since after} Nc6 {the White knight will probably have to go back to c3 sooner or later.}) ({In the next game, White tried} 12. Nb5 Nxb5 13. cxb5 {[%csl Ga2,Gb2,Gb5] and such an unusual pawn structure appeared. However, by playing accurately in the center, Black equalized the game.} d5 $1 14. exd5 Qxd5 15. f3 Be6 16. Qe2 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ya8c8,Yf8d8,Yd7e7] is OK for Black 1-0 (45) Almasi,Z (2650)-Chatalbashev,B (2535) Krynica 1998}) 12... Be6 (12... a5 $6 {[%csl Gb5] looks logical. Black wants to stop the White pawn. But this plan is dubious because Black hasn't a6-b5 plan anymore.} 13. Nb5 Bd7 14. Bxd4 Bxb5 (14... exd4 {is better} 15. Nxd6 Bxa4 16. Qxa4 Qxd6 17. f4 $14 {but this position is unpleasant for Black}) 15. Be3 (15. cxb5 $5 exd4 16. Bc4 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ga1c1] In this pawn stucture White bishop is much better, then Black bishop on g7.}) 15... Bc6 16. f3 f5 17. Qc2 $16 {and White won it : 1-0 (35) Van Wely,L (2663)-Edouard,R (2640) Chartres 2017}) ({After} 12... b6 13. Nb5 {White is better} a6 (13... Nc6 14. Be2 Be6 15. Qxd6 Qxd6 16. Nxd6 Rfd8 17. Nb5 $14 {White keeps an extra pawn}) (13... Nxb5 14. axb5 $14 {[%csl Ga7] here Black pawn on a7 is very weak}) 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bf4 $14 {White'sWhite's pawn structure is better. Black doesn't have enough counterplay.}) ({The next game shows how White plays in this structure.} 12... a6 13. a5 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd1a4] At the beginning, White took over the space and prepared the a4 square for his queen.} Be6 14. Qa4 Rc8 15. Nd5 $1 {White is ready to change the structure and capture even more space.} Bxd5 16. cxd5 {[%cal Yc1c8]} ({Of course, after} 16. exd5 Qh4 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black is fine}) 16... Rc5 17. Rfc1 {and now it is very difficult for Black to defend the weaknesses in the center and on the queenside. In the game, White won it easily.} Qe7 18. Rxc5 dxc5 19. Rc1 Rd8 20. Qc4 Bf8 21. f4 $1 Qf6 22. b4 exf4 23. Rf1 b5 24. axb6 Qxb6 25. Bxf4 Qxb4 26. Qxa6 Nb3 27. Be5 Be7 28. Qa7 c4 29. d6 Re8 30. Qd7 Qb6+ 31. Kh1 Qd8 32. Bxc4 {1-0 (32) Shabalov,A (2615)-Baburin,A (2600) Mermaid Beach 1998}) 13. a5 {White continues his plan. Black tried different moves here.} ({In the next game, Black equalized after} 13. Nb5 $6 a6 $1 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bd2 Rc8 16. Rc1 f5 $1 $11 {½-½ (22) Ferreira,J (2499)-Edouard,R (2607) Belgium BEL 2018} 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Qb3 Qd7 $132 {[%cal Ge8e2,Gc8c4]}) 13... Qd7 (13... f5 {this active counterplay is insufficient for equality. Black still has weak pawns in the center.} 14. exf5 Nxf5 ({After} 14... gxf5 15. Bxd4 $1 exd4 16. Nd5 Kh8 17. g3 Qd7 18. Re1 $16 {Black's position is just bad.}) 15. Qe2 Kh8 16. Be4 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5][%cal Gd1d6] preparing an attack against the "d" pawn} Nxe3 17. fxe3 Rxf1+ 18. Qxf1 Qe7 19. Qe2 Rf8 20. b3 $14 {White controls the position, he has better chances.}) ({After} 13... b6 {White grabs more space and slowly improves his position. He prepares Nb5.} 14. a6 {[%cal Gc3b5]} Rc8 15. b3 Qh4 16. Re1 Bg4 17. f3 Be6 18. Bf1 Rfd8 19. Rb1 Qe7 20. Qd2 Rc5 21. Red1 $14 {[%cal Gc3b5] White improved his position, Nb5 is coming}) 14. Qa4 {We'll watch the game Saric-Navara, Batumi, 2018. White changes queens and wants to play a better endgame. Black needs to keep an eye on his weaknesses on the queenside.} Qxa4 (14... Qe7 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. cxd5 $14 {[%cal Gc1c7] offers better position for White}) 15. Rxa4 Rfc8 16. Nd5 {grabs more space} Bxd5 (16... Kf8 17. Bg5 $14) 17. exd5 (17. cxd5 $14 {[%cal Ga4b4,Gf1c1] is also fine. White wants to play Rc1 or Rb4.}) 17... Re8 18. Re1 f5 19. Kf1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5] White prepares the play on the queenside by b4-c5. His position is better. 1-0 (67) Saric,I (2657)-Navara,D (2737) Batumi 2018 Сonclusion: "The е5 structure" is very interesting. It promises a rich strategic battle. White must control the game in the center and prepare a breakthrough on the queenside. Black tries to start an active counterplay after a6-b5 or f5. Understanding this structure is very important, as it appears not only in this variation, but also in many other openings.} *

[Event "?"]
