[White "Chapter 5 - Exchange on \"d5\""]
[Black "White Captures with the \"e\" p"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Romanov"]
[ECO "B38"]
[PlyCount "63"]
[GameId "2134713424064716"]
[EventDate "2025.01.30"]

{[%evp 0,63,19,31,72,53,93,79,81,85,75,34,32,22,26,20,20,34,34,31,27,30,39,40,40,45,71,63,47,33,43,4,53,32,36,37,39,25,37,7,4,13,61,63,83,83,75,75,83,81,97,73,69,56,84,84,73,77,86,77,70,81,89,93,77,84] In this chapter, we will look at the pawn structure that occurs after the White knight is exchanged for d5. We will be interested in the structures in which White opens the "e" file. Another important pawn structure, which is the capture of the "c" pawn, will be discussed in another chapter. After ed, White gets big space advantage, control over the "e" line, and the opportunity to attack the backward Black pawn on e7. The following plans can be noted for White: 1) playing in the center against the e7 pawn; 2) playing on the kingside, especially after exchanging dark-square bishops; 3) playing on the queenside by b4-c5. The first two plans are most common since the third plan gives Black opportunities to counterplay. The main plans of the Blacks: 1) b5 break; 2) pressure on the queenside after a5-a4; 3) exchanging pieces, ideally Black would like to get a knight against White'sWhite's light-square bishop with White pawns on light squares; 4) e6 break and exchanging of his weak pawn. This structure occurs in different orders of moves, so here we will look at typical games on this topic without reference to a specific opening variation.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 (2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 (5... Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. f3 d6 9. Qd2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. exd5 Bd7 {Our structure has emerged. White is castling to the queenside to make a typical attack on the kingside more dangerous. With the king on c1, White can afford to move all the kingside pawns. [#]} 14. h4 $5 $40 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh4h5,Ge1c1]} h5 15. O-O-O Qb6 $6 (15... e6 $5 {[%cal Yc8c1] was better} 16. dxe6 Bxe6 17. g4 Rh8 $1 $13 {with unclear fight}) 16. g4 hxg4 17. Re1 Rae8 18. h5 $1 Rh8 19. Bd3 Qd4 20. Re4 Qf6 21. fxg4 e5 22. dxe6 Rxe6 23. Rf4 Qe7 24. Rhf1 $18 {White has revealed the position and Black is defenseless.} Be8 25. hxg6 fxg6 26. Qc3+ Re5 27. c5 d5 28. Kb1 Qg5 29. Bf5 Kf6 30. R4f3 Rh7 31. Re1 Rhe7 32. Bd7+ Kg7 33. Rfe3 Bxd7 34. Rxe5 Rxe5 35. Rxe5 Qxg4 36. Re4+ {1-0 (36) Krasenkow,M (2632)-Managadze,N (2463) Aghia Pelagia 2004. White won a good game, but more often, White does not have time to make a long castle.}) 6. Nc3 d6 7. f3 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 a5 11. b3 Be6 12. Rc1 Nd7 13. Be2 Nc5 14. O-O Qb6 15. Nb5 (15. Rc2 Rfc8 16. Kh1 Qb4 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Na6 19. Qc1 {Our structure has emerged. But here White does not have any advantage, because White did not have time to create a game in the center, and Black has already occupied the Black fields and is ready for active play. How to play? [#]} a4 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4] It is a time for queenside play!} 20. Bd2 Qc5 21. Qe1 ({After} 21. Be3 {Black can decline a draw offer} Bd4 $5 {this trade is usually in Black's favor} 22. Bxd4 Qxd4 23. Rd1 Qb6 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga6c5] White is under pressure}) 21... axb3 22. axb3 b5 (22... Qb6 {[%cal Ga6c5,Ga8a2] was also fine, Black prepares Nc5 and Ra2} 23. b4 Nc7 24. Rc1 Ra2 $132 {with counterplay}) 23. b4 Qd4 24. Qc1 bxc4 25. Bxc4 Qb6 26. Qa3 Nc7 27. Qd3 Nb5 $15 {In the game, the opening of the queenside was in Black's favor. He is getting better. Therefore, White must carry out the plan of advancing the queenside pawns very carefully. White managed to defend himself in the following game.} 28. Rfc1 Na3 29. Ra2 Nxc4 30. Rxc4 Qb7 31. Rxc8+ Rxc8 32. g3 h5 33. h3 Qb6 34. Kg2 Be5 35. f4 Bf6 36. g4 Bh4 37. Bc3 Qb7 38. Ra5 hxg4 39. hxg4 Bf6 40. Bd2 e6 41. Rb5 Qa8 42. Ra5 Qb7 43. Rb5 Qa8 44. Ra5 {1/2 (44) Predke,A (2530)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2630) Moscow 2015}) 15... Bd7 16. Rfd1 Rfc8 17. Bf1 Qd8 18. Nc3 Bc6 19. Qf2 Qf8 20. Nd5 Nd7 21. Qh4 Bxd5 22. exd5 {Our structure has emerged. White also starts to carry out a queenside plan in the game, and Black gets a good game.[#]} Rc7 23. Qf2 Rac8 24. a3 {[%cal Yb3b4]} Ra8 25. Rb1 {[%cal Gb3b4] Objectively, White's position is still better, but from a practical point of view, after opening the queenside, Black's pieces will receive active squares, and it will be easier for White to make a mistake.} Nc5 26. Rdc1 Bh6 $5 {looking for a good trade} 27. f4 Bg7 28. b4 Nd7 29. Rc2 axb4 30. axb4 Ra3 31. Be2 Qa8 $1 {[%csl Rb4,Rc4,Rd5][%cal Ga8a4] and Black is not worse anymore} 32. c5 Qa4 (32... Ra2 $1 $15 {exchangings are in Black's favor}) 33. Bd1 Qb5 34. Be2 Qa4 35. Bd1 Qb5 36. Be2 Qa4 {1/2 (36) Paravyan,D (2478)-Motylev,A (2643) Kaliningrad 2015}) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nc6 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O {Now let's look at the first two plans for White.} Bd7 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bd7 11. f4 Bc6 12. Bf3 Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd2 a5 15. Rad1 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Rfd8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 {[%csl Re7,Rg7][%cal Ge1e7,Gf4f5] A starting position has appeared. White begins to carry out the most dangerous plan- an attack on the Black king. Due to the lack of space, it is difficult for Black to protect the king.[#]} Rac8 19. b3 a4 20. Qc3+ Kg8 21. Rde1 {[%csl Re7] Weak pawn is under attack.} axb3 22. axb3 Re8 23. Bg4 {[%csl Gd7]} Qc7 $2 {the last mistake} (23... f5 $1 {was the only move} 24. Bf3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gg2g4] White should prepare h3-g4 with a dangerous attack.} Nf6 25. h3 Qc7 26. g4 b5 27. gxf5 bxc4 28. fxg6 cxb3 29. gxh7+ Kh8 30. Qxb3 Qc3 $44 {The computer fights back, but it's difficult for a human to find it.}) 24. f5 $1 $18 f6 (24... g5 {is an interesting try} 25. Qe3 f6 26. h4 Ne5 {[%csl Gd6,Re5,Ge7,Gf6,Gg5] it is another very important pawn structure! Black wants to put all his pawns on dark squares. It would be very hard for White to attack Black's position without knights. At the same time, Black knight takes a great position on e5.[#] however, after} 27. Bh5 $1 {Black is not in time} Rf8 28. hxg5 $18 {wins} ({Just an example.} 28. Ra1 $2 {after} h6 $1 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Ye5,Ge7,Gf6,Gg5,Gh6] only Black can be better here. Remember this fundamental pawn structure!})) 25. fxg6 hxg6 26. Qh3 {in the game, Shirov won easily} f5 27. Bxf5 $1 gxf5 28. Rxf5 {[%csl Rg8]} Nf6 29. Rg5+ Kf7 30. Qe6+ Kf8 31. Rf1 {[%cal Gg5g8] 1-0 (31) Shirov,A (2714)-Leon Hoyos,M (2548) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 10. Qd2 ({In the next game, we will see another good example of White'sWhite's attack on the kingside.} 10. Nc2 $5 {This is an interesting opening setup. White has more space, so he keeps more pieces on the board. We will discuss this opening variation in more detail in another chapter, but here we will focus on the pawn structure that interests us.} a6 11. f3 Be6 12. Qd2 a5 13. b3 Nd7 14. Rac1 Nc5 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Ne5 {Our structure has emerged. Unlike the previous examples, White has kept three minor pieces. This circumstance increases White'sWhite's advantage. In addition, Black has problems with active counterplay.} 17. Nd4 {The first part of White'sWhite's plan is to improve the position of his pieces. White puts everything in the center.} Ned7 18. Rb1 Nf6 19. Rfd1 Qd7 20. Bf1 Rfc8 21. Re1 Re8 22. Rbd1 Qd8 23. Nb5 Qd7 {Black can only stand and wait. The first part of the plan is completed. How can White improve his position?[#]} 24. g3 $1 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gh2h5] Very strong, but typical plan. White prepares to develop the bishop on h3. Then it will be possible to start moving the pawns on the kingside.} Qc8 25. Bd4 Qd7 (25... Nfd7 26. Be3 Ne5 27. Kg2 Qd8 28. Be2 {[%cal Gf3f4]} Qc8 29. f4 Ned7 30. Bf3 {[%cal Gg3g4]}) 26. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg1h2,Gf1h3] the start of the attack} a4 27. b4 $1 Na6 28. Kh2 Qd8 29. a3 {[%csl Ra4] Black tried to create counterplay, but got an additional weakness on a4.} Nd7 30. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[#]} 31. h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g6,Rh5h6] White is ready to attack} Nc7 32. h6+ $5 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gc3g7] Also a very typical move in attack on the kingside fianchetto. The White pawn takes away the square on the 7th row. White gets the idea Qc3-Qg7#.} Kg8 33. Qb2 Nf6 34. Nxc7 Qxc7 {White has a decisive advantage. How to win?[#]} 35. Re3 $1 {[%csl Ge7,Rg8] White uses the principle of two weaknesses. Black cannot simultaneously protect the weakness on e7 and his king.} Qc8 36. Bh3 Qxc4 37. Rde1 {[%cal Gb2f6,Ge3e8] The rest is easy.} Kf8 38. Bd7 $1 Rec8 39. Bxc8 Rxc8 40. Rxe7 Qc2+ 41. Qxc2 Rxc2+ 42. Kh3 {1-0 (42) Bachmann,A (2644)-Wang,P (2449) Tromsoe 2014. It's a very instructive game. White demonstrated an understanding of this pawn structure.}) ({In the next game, Black demonstrated a typical defensive plan that involves changing the pawn structure.} 10. Rc1 {is not the best plan because Black manages to exchange many pieces} Nxd4 $1 11. Bxd4 Bc6 $1 {[%cal Yf6d7] preparing d7 square for a knight} 12. f3 Nd7 13. Kh1 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qb6 {Queen's trade is also in Black's favor.} 15. Qd2 Nc5 16. Rfe1 Rad8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 {[%cal Gb2b4] Our structure has emerged.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb4] space is very important for Black} 19. Bf1 Rfe8 20. Re3 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge3e7,Gc1e1] The position is approximately equal. White prepares pressure along the e-file. How to play Black?[#]} e5 $1 {exchanging the weak pawn on e7} 21. dxe6 Rxe6 {The Black knight is stronger than the White bishop, the weak pawn on d6 is very difficult to use. Black's plan includes further exchanges of pieces and an attack on the weak pawns on the queenside} 22. Rce1 (22. Rxe6 Nxe6 23. b3 Qb4 $13 {is ok for Black}) 22... Qb4 $1 23. Qf2 (23. Qxb4 axb4 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2,Gb4,Gb7,Rc4] is a bad pawn structure for White bishop}) 23... Rde8 24. Rxe6 Rxe6 $15 {Black strives for a queen+knight versus queen+bishop ratio.} 25. Rd1 Qa4 26. b3 Qb4 27. Kg1 {How to play?[#]} a4 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rb3,Rc4] Creating new weaknesses for White.} 28. bxa4 Qxa4 29. Rd2 Qb4 30. Rb2 Qc3 $15 {[%csl Ra2,Rc4] Black's pawn structure is already better. White has no obvious counterplay. Black gradually won it.} 31. Qd2 Qf6 32. Rb1 h5 33. Re1 Rxe1 34. Qxe1 Qe5 35. Qf2 Kf8 36. g3 h4 37. gxh4 Ne6 38. Qd2 Nd4 39. Kg2 Nf5 40. Qf2 Qf4 41. Kh3 Nxh4 42. Qg3 Qf6 43. f4 Nf5 44. Qe1 Qd4 45. Kg2 {0-1 (45) Tukmakov,V-Velimirovic,D Odessa 1975. А great game showing Black's defensive capabilities!}) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {Now let's look at this structure in the main variation of this opening.} Bc6 12. f3 a5 13. b3 Nd7 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Rab1 Qb6 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 17. Rc2 Qd8 18. Bf1 {This is all opening theory. Black's position is rather unpleasant.} Qf8 {[%cal Yh7h5,Yg8h7,Yg7h6] One of the ideas of this move is to exchange bishops on h6} 19. Kh1 ({In the next game, White managed to pin Black to the ground all over the board.} 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 {Our structure has emerged.[#]} Rc7 21. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] White prepares to grab space on the queenside and, at the same time, causes weaknesses on the kingside.} b6 22. Bg5 h6 23. Be3 {[%csl Rh6]} g5 {[%csl Rg5,Rh6][%cal Gf3f4] Not a good change in pawn structure for Black. In the future White will play f4 and open up the kingside for attack.} 24. Qf2 Rb7 {How to play?[#]} 25. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gf3f4] typical improvement} Bf6 26. b4 axb4 27. axb4 Nd7 28. Bh3 Ne5 29. f4 $18 {White played f4, Black collaps.} Nd3 30. Qe2 gxf4 31. gxf4 Qg7+ 32. Kh1 Qh7 33. Rg1+ Kh8 34. Qh5 e6 35. Rcg2 Re7 36. dxe6 fxe6 37. Rg6 Bg7 38. Bxe6 {1-0 (38) Khalifman,A (2690)-Berndt,S (2482) Kallithea 2002. A convincing victory!}) 19... Be5 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 {Our structure has emerged. Let's see how White improved in this game.[#]} Qg7 22. Re1 {[%csl Re7] White increases pressure along the e-file.} Rc7 23. g3 $1 {[%cal Yf1h3] A familiar move, White prepares to improve the bishop.} f5 {[%csl Rf5,Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gg3g4] now the kingside is weakened} ({if Black waits, then White doubles up on the e-file, then advances the kingside pawns} 23... Bf6 24. Bh3 Qf8 25. Rcc1 Qg7 26. Re2 {[%cal Yc1e1]} Qf8 27. g4 Bg7 28. g5 $16 {[%csl Re7,Rg8][%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5]}) 24. Bh6 Qf7 25. Bh3 Bg7 26. Bg5 Bf6 27. Be3 Be5 28. f4 Bf6 {[#]} 29. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg1g8] using the Black pawn position} fxg4 30. Bxg4 Qg7 31. Rg1 Kh8 32. f5 $18 {[%cal Gg1g7] And the White attack is very dangerous. 1-0 (61) Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Jones,G (2679) Chess.com INT 2020. It's another typical game for this pawn structure. Conclusion: We have covered the main plans typical for the "Nd5-ed" pawn structure. A detailed study of the games presented will improve your understanding of such positions significantly.} *

