{[%evp 0,57,19,38,40,41,51,18,45,29,92,28,34,32,70,33,32,26,15,6,6,-1,54,47,56,50,59,29,46,36,58,47,53,59,82,76,80,75,81,63,75,51,64,64,61,67,67,30,95,67,107,118,126,122,126,131,155,183,194,205] In this chapter, we will look at the pawn structure that occurs after White plays Nd5 and beats cd to capture. In this case, there is a symmetrical pawn position in which White has more space. It is very important. Due to the advantage in space, White can often improve his position without the risk of losing. White's plan calls for gradually strengthening the pieces and a further seizure of space after a4-b4-a5 and f4-g4-g5. With a significant space advantage, White can prepare pawn breakthroughs on all parts of the board. Black plans to exchange pieces or pawn counterplay( a5-a4 or f5). It is important that if Black does not have time to create an active game immediately, then they will have a long and difficult defense. The more pieces there are on the board, Black's position will be worse. We will look at this pawn structure in the middlegame and in various endgames using the example of the following games.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 ({In this game, we will see an example of a successful counterattack by Black.} 6... Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. f3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 a5 12. Qd2 Bc6 13. b3 Nd7 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Rab1 Qb6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board. How to play?[#]} Qb4 $1 {Of course, Black wants to trade his queen.} 18. Rfd1 (18. a4 {is another move here}) (18. Qxb4 $2 {is bad} axb4 $19 {[%csl Ra2]}) 18... Rfc8 19. Rbc1 Qxd2 20. Bxd2 {What to do now? White needs just one move to get an advantage. [#]} a4 $1 {An active counterplay! That's the only way Black can even the game.} ({in case of slow} 20... h5 21. Bb5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gb5a4,Ra5a4] a4 is not possible anymore}) 21. bxa4 ({A very important idea arises after} 21. b4 {[#]} Nb3 $1 {[%cal Ga4a1] another active move} 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Bf4 (23. axb3 $2 {is bad} a3 $19 {[%cal Ga3a1]}) 23... Bb2 24. Kf1 Nc1 {equalizing completely} 25. Bxc1 $11 {1/2 (25) Battaglia,R (2157)-Garcia Rodriguez,I (2216) ICCF email 2015}) 21... Bb2 22. Rc4 Rxa4 23. Rxa4 Nxa4 {[%cal Ga4c3]} 24. Kf1 Nc3 25. Bxc3 Rxc3 $11 {Black has changed most of the pieces, his position is great. Then Black even managed to win. 0-1 (75) Bachmann,A (2644)-Le,Q (2710) Tromsoe 2014}) 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be2 (8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 Be6 ({In the next game, we'll look at the endgame with rooks and minor pieces. Having rooks gives White more attacking opportunities.} 9... O-O 10. Qd2 a5 11. b3 Bd7 12. Be2 Bc6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfd1 Nc5 15. Rac1 Qb6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board.} Qb4 $5 {He wants to trade his queen.} 18. Rc2 (18. Qxb4 $6 {is bad. After} axb4 19. Rc2 Ra3 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Yf8a8] Black has an excelent play}) 18... Qxd2 19. Bxd2 h5 {[%cal Yg8h7,Yg7h6] This is a very typical idea. After Kh7-Bh6 Black wants to trade dark-square bishops. The endgame "light-square bishop against knight" should be OK for Black.} 20. Bb5 Kh7 21. Bg5 {[%csl Ge7] it is a good idea to create him a new weakness} f6 22. Be3 Bh6 {What to do now?[#]} 23. Bxc5 $5 {An interesting attempt. White brings the game to an endgame with opposit-color bishops. White's plan is to move the pawns in the center. Black's pawns are blocked, they have no counterplay.} (23. Bxh6 $6 Kxh6 $14 {Black's position is very solid.}) 23... dxc5 24. Kf2 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4,Ge4e5,Gd5d6] because of the extra pawn in the center, White has a big advantage.} Rac8 25. g3 Rfd8 26. f4 g5 27. Kf3 gxf4 28. gxf4 e5 29. fxe5 fxe5 30. d6 Rf8+ 31. Ke2 Rf4 32. d7 Rcf8 33. Kd3 b6 34. Rg2 Rd8 35. Kc3 Rf6 36. Kc4 Bf4 37. Rd3 Kh6 38. Kd5 h4 39. Rh3 Bg5 40. Kxe5 {1-0 (40) Khismatullin,D (2671)-Vorobiov,E (2587) Vladivostok 2014}) 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Qd2 Qa5 12. b3 ({The next game is a good example of Black's active counterplay.} 12. Bd3 Rfc8 13. b3 a6 14. Ne2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nd7 16. Nf4 Nc5 17. Be2 a5 18. Nd5 $6 Bxd5 19. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board. Black starts thematic play on the queenside. [#]} a4 $1 {[%csl Ya2,Yb3] Now Black is doing well, but White is skipping tactics} 20. b4 $2 {[#]} (20. Bxc5 {was necessary} axb3 21. axb3 Ra2+ 22. Kd3 dxc5 23. Rc2 Ra3 $15 {but only Black plays here for a win.}) 20... Nb3+ $3 {[%cal Yg7a1,Ra4a1] Black's pawn became too strong.} 21. axb3 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 a3 23. Bb5 a2 24. Kd3 a1=Q 25. Rxa1 Rxa1 $17 {Black converted his advantage. 0-1 (58) Polgar,J (2665)-Antunes,A (2540) Yerevan 1996}) 12... a6 13. Nd5 {In this game, we will see how White converts the advantage in the middelgame.} Qd8 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. Be2 Bxd5 16. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board. In the middegame, Black does not have enough squares for his pieces. White has a very unpleasant plan to occupy the space further.[#]} Rfc8 17. O-O Qe8 18. Be3 Nd7 19. g3 Nc5 $6 {Black chose a bad plan. It was necessary to simplify the position by making changes along the "c "line.} (19... Rxc1 20. Rxc1 Rc8 $14 {[%cal Gc8c1] was better}) 20. Rc2 a5 21. Rfc1 b6 22. Qd1 Qf8 {White improved all his pieces. The Black pieces are cramped. How to play?[#]} 23. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb3b4,Yc2c8] The right plan. White opens the queenside and exploits Black's weaknesses.} Rcb8 (23... Nxb3 $2 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Rxc8 Qxc8 26. Qxb3 $18 {wins for White}) 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Nb3 $2 {Loses immediately} (25... Nd7 {It was better} 26. Bb5 Qd8 27. Kg2 $16 {But Black has a very difficult position.}) 26. Rb1 Ra3 27. Rc6 $18 {[%csl Rb6]} Na1 28. Bxb6 {now White promotes the "b" pawn to the queen} f5 29. Bd4 Rba8 30. e5 Bxe5 31. Bxe5 dxe5 32. b5 e4 33. b6 exf3 34. Bxf3 Qh6 35. b7 Qe3+ 36. Kh1 Kf7 37. bxa8=Q Rxa8 38. d6 {1-0 (38) Smeets,J (2618)-Tiviakov,S (2665) Netherlands 2013. This game shows how important it is for Black to trade pieces in a right moment.}) ({In the next two games, we'll look at a minor-pieces endgame. Most often, White has the advantage of two bishops. His plan is to take more space. It is tough for Black to find a counterplay, usually he has to stand and wait.} 8. Bg5 Bg7 9. Qd2 Be6 10. Rc1 Qa5 11. f3 O-O 12. Be2 Rfc8 13. b3 Rab8 (13... a6 14. Na4 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Rc6 16. Nc3 Kf8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board.} Rcc8 $1 {An important moment.} ({After} 18... Rxc1 $2 19. Rxc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] White controls "c" file.} Ke8 20. Rc7 Rb8 21. Be3 $18 {[%cal Ye3a7] and it is winning for White.}) 19. Be3 Nd7 20. Rxc8+ Rxc8 21. Rc1 Rxc1 22. Kxc1 {[%cal Yb3b4,Ya2a4,Yb4b5,Yg2g4,Yh2h4,Yg4g5] A minor-figured endgame has emerged.[#]} Ke8 23. Kc2 Kd8 24. b4 {capturing the space on the queenside} h6 25. g3 g5 {[%csl Rg5,Rh6][%cal Gf3f4] a controversial decision. Black is trying to capture at least some space, but creates weaknesses on the kingside. In another game we will see the g6-h7 pawn structure.} ({The computer offers} 25... e6 26. dxe6 fxe6 $16 {but the opening of the center is in favor of White.}) 26. a4 (26. f4 $5 {It deserved attention} gxf4 27. Bxf4 Nf6 28. Bf3 $16 {[%cal Yg3g5,Yh2h4] and then g4-h4-g5.}) 26... Nf6 27. Bd4 Kc7 28. f4 gxf4 29. gxf4 Nh5 {looking for trades} 30. Be3 $1 Nf6 31. Bf3 Nd7 32. a5 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7] Black has a very dangerous position.} f5 $5 {looking for a fortress. White won the pawn, but did not find a way to win the game.} 33. exf5 Ba1 34. Bh5 b5 35. Bf7 Bf6 36. Be6 Kd8 37. Bf7 Kc7 38. Kd2 Kd8 39. Kd3 Kc7 40. Bf2 Kd8 41. Be1 Bb2 42. Be6 Kc7 43. Bd2 Nf6 44. Be3 Kb7 45. Bb6 Nh5 46. Bf7 Nxf4+ 47. Kc2 {Black withstood a very unpleasant defense. 1/2 (47) Vallejo Pons,F (2662)-Malakhov,V (2696) Selfoss 2003.}) 14. Nd5 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bxd5 16. cxd5 {Our pawn structure is on the board.} Kf8 17. Be3 {[%csl Ya7]} Ra8 18. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] It is a good idea to grab more space.} Nd7 19. Rxc8+ Rxc8 20. Rc1 Rxc1 21. Kxc1 {[%cal Gh2h5,Gb3b4,Ga2a5] We got minor-pieces endgame. White improves his pieces and grabs more space.} a6 22. Kc2 Ke8 ({The computer is fighting for space} 22... h6 $5 {against g5} 23. h4 e6 $5 24. dxe6 fxe6 25. f4 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Re6,Rg6,Rh6] According to computer, it is better for Black than the position in the game. However, White is the strongest side anyway.}) 23. g5 $5 {[%csl Gf7,Gg6,Gh7][%cal Rg5f6,Rg5h6] White fixes the kingside.} Nc5 (23... e6 24. dxe6 fxe6 25. f4) 24. b4 $5 {[%cal Ga2a5,Gb4b5] now we need to capture the space on the queenside} Na4 25. b5 Nc5 26. bxa6 bxa6 {[%csl Ra6] The pawn is a new weakness. Now White improves his kingside.} (26... Nxa6 27. Kb3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c4,Gc4b5,Gh2h5] White king comes to b5.}) 27. h4 Kd8 28. Bf1 Kc7 29. Bh3 Nd7 30. Bf1 Nc5 31. Bh3 Nd7 32. f4 $1 {grabing more space} h6 {Blacks have an unpleasant choice. After this move, he exchanges at least one pawn.} ({If Black waits, then White gradually breaks through in the center. For example,} 32... Bh8 33. Kb3 Bg7 34. Kb4 Nc5 35. e5 $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge5e6,Gf4f5]}) 33. Bf1 hxg5 34. hxg5 Kb7 35. Be2 Ba1 36. Kb1 Bc3 37. Kc2 Ba5 38. Bg4 Bb6 $6 {it loses immediately} ({But after} 38... Nc5 39. e5 Bb6 40. e6 $16) ({or} 38... Kc7 39. Bd4 Bb6 40. Kd3 Kd8 41. e5 $16 {Black's position is very hard to play.}) 39. Bxb6 Nxb6 40. Kb3 {[%csl Gf7,Gg6] Blacks has too many weaknesses. In addition, White plays e5 creating new ones.} Na8 41. Bd7 {[%csl Yf7,Yg6]} Nc7 42. f5 Kb6 43. Kc4 Kb7 44. a4 Kb6 45. Bc6 Ka7 46. Kc3 Kb6 47. Kb4 a5+ 48. Kc4 Ka6 49. Kd4 Kb6 50. Bd7 Kb7 51. fxg6 fxg6 52. e5 $1 dxe5+ 53. Kxe5 Kb6 54. Be6 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Ye6f7] 1-0 (54) Lutz,C (2575)-Schlosser,P (2500) Dresden 1995. It's a very instructive game. In the end, Black lost because of White'sWhite's large space advantage.}) 8... Bg7 9. Be3 ({In this game, we will see that Black is even willing to compromise with his pawn structure in order to exchange pieces.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe3 Be6 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. b3 Qxe3 13. Bxe3 Nd7 14. Rac1 Nc5 15. f3 Rfc8 16. Rfd1 a5 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. cxd5 {We got our pawn structure.} Bb2 19. Rc2 Ba3 20. Bb5 {White is ready for the next improvement. What to do now?[#]} Na6 $1 {[%cal Gc8c2] A very strong reply. Black has less space, so he is looking for simplifications.} (20... Kg7 21. Rdd2 $14 {[%cal Gg1f2] and White is better}) 21. Rxc8+ Rxc8 22. Bxa6 bxa6 {[%csl Ra5,Ra6][%cal Ga5a4] It looks like Black pawns are weak, but after a4 Blach equalizes immediately.} 23. Kf1 f6 24. Ke2 a4 $1 25. Kd3 axb3 26. axb3 Rb8 27. Rb1 Kf7 $11 {1/2 (27) Izoria,Z (2646)-Tiviakov,S (2700) Pamplona 2005. Good defensive strategy!}) ({In this game, we will see an example of Black's active counterplay in the middelgame.} 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Qd2 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] typical idea to grab more space on the queenside} 11. O-O a4 12. Rac1 Bd7 13. Rfd1 Bc6 14. f3 Nd7 15. Rc2 Nc5 16. Rb1 Re8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board.} Qb6 19. Be3 (19. Kh1 {was more accurate}) 19... Rec8 20. b4 $6 {White did not prepare well enough for this active game. First of all, it was worth making several prophylactic moves to prevent a direct counterplay by Black.} axb3 21. axb3 {How to play now?[#]} Bh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6d2,Gb6g1] The White king gets hit.} 22. Qd4 Bxe3+ 23. Qxe3 $1 Ra3 {[%csl Gb3] Black made a profitable exchange of bishops. Now the "b" pawn becomes weak. A White bishop is much worse than a Black knight.} 24. Rc3 Rca8 25. Qd4 Ra1 26. Rcc1 Rxb1 27. Rxb1 Ra2 $15 {[%csl Rb3,Gc5,Re2][%cal Ga2g2] There are many weaknesses in White'sWhite's position, and he faces a difficult defense. In the game, White lost. 0-1 (55) Strikovic,A (2526)-Dvirnyy,D (2540) Tortoreto 2015. A very good example of Black's strategy.}) 9... O-O 10. Qd2 a5 ({In the next game, we will look at Black's attempt to escape a difficult space situation.} 10... Be6 11. O-O Qa5 12. Rab1 Rfc8 13. b3 a6 14. Rfc1 Qb4 15. f3 Nd7 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Bxd2 Bxd5 18. cxd5 {Our structure is on the board.} Bd4+ 19. Kf1 Nb6 20. f4 {[#]} e6 {An interesting attempt to reduce the White advantage in space.} 21. dxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Rd6,Re6] but this pawn structure turns out to be even more difficult for Black. White has two strong bishops. They benefit from the showdown of the game.[#]} 22. Bf3 {slow improvement} Rc6 (22... d5 {Playing in the center further enhances the bishops} 23. Ke2 dxe4 24. Bxe4 Nd5 25. g3 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Ge4,Re6]}) (22... Kf7 {If Black is waiting, then White is preparing a breakthrough in the center.} 23. Ke2 Nd7 24. g4 $16 {[%cal Gf4f5,Ye4e5]}) 23. Rxc6 bxc6 24. Ba5 Nd7 25. Rd1 {[%csl Rd6]} e5 26. Bc7 Rf8 27. Bxd6 Rxf4 28. Rxd4 Rxf3+ 29. gxf3 exd4 30. Ke2 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rd4][%cal Ge2d3] a difficult endgame that Black lost 1-0 (58) Morovic Fernandez,I (2580)-Spangenberg,H (2550) Buenos Aires 1997. A good example of what awaits Black when trying to vacate his position in the center.}) 11. f3 a4 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Rc2 Bd7 14. O-O Bc6 15. Rfc1 Nd7 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Qxa5 $1 Rxa5 18. cxd5 {[%cal Gc2c7,Gb2b4] Our pawn structure is on the board. White is better because of the advantage in space and the better pieces.} Nc5 19. Kf1 b6 20. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] planning b4 later} f5 {Black is trying to start a fight in the center. If he can not find any counterplay White will grabe more space. In this case, Black's position will become even worse.} (20... h5 {a waiting move} 21. Bg5 {[%cal Yb2b4] preparing b4} ({It's bad to play like that right away} 21. b4 $2 axb3 22. axb3 Ra3 $1 $132 {[%csl Re3]}) 21... Ra7 22. b4 axb3 23. axb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3b4] White is better}) 21. exf5 Rxf5 {Black simplified the situation a bit, but it's even worse for him.} (21... gxf5 22. g3 Kf7 23. Kg2 $16 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7,Gf5][%cal Gc2c4,Gc4a4,Gc4h4] There are now many pawn weaknesses in Black's position that White can exploit after Rc4.}) 22. Rd1 Ra8 23. h4 {White is planning to capture the space on the kingside further.} a3 $2 {unsuccessful counterplay attempt, now White wins forced.} ({It was necessary to wait} 23... Be5 24. g4 Rf7 25. Kg2 Raf8 $14 {[%cal Yf3f4,Re5f4,Rf8f4] And it's not so easy for White to strengthen further.}) 24. b4 Na4 25. Rd3 {[%csl Ra3,Rb6] Now it is just bad for Black.} Nb2 26. Rb3 Rxd5 27. Bxb6 Rb8 28. Ba7 $1 Rb7 29. Be3 $18 {[%cal Gb4b5] As usual, the showdown turned out to be in White'sWhite's favor, White won. 1-0 (48) Polgar,J (2699)-Mamedov,R (2679) Ningbo 2011. The game shows how difficult it is for Black to get enough counterplay. Conclusion: We have reviewed the key plans in this pawn structure. Black has a big problem if he doesn't start a counterplay immediately. White will have the advantage both in the middlegame and in all endgames.} *

