{[%evp 0,41,19,-12,11,14,8,1,-5,-41,0,18,23,23,51,41,35,-14,8,19,7,20,19,13,44,32,35,14,10,16,20,15,25,11,31,43,54,36,53,58,64,64,51,46] In this chapter, we will look at the endgame that occurs in the classical Maroczy structure. At the same time, after the exchange of queens, there is no change in the pawn structure. This usually happens if White meets the Qa5 move with the Na4 move. After the exchange of queens, there is a classic endgame with space advantage for White. White's plans: 1) capturing the space on the kingside after g4-h4-h5; 2) strengthening the position and preparing for Black's counterplay; 3) transferring the knight to d5, after which the pawn structure will be changed to the options already considered. Black's main plan is to play a6-b5 with a counterplay on the queenside. Sometimes Black tries to play in the center by e6 or f5. In general, the assessment of such endgames is in favor of White, but Black's position is very solid. For the convenience of studying, we will consider such endgame, which appears in the next opening line.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 g6 6. e4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 11. Rc1 {Now Black's main try is} Qa5 ({A usual plan that doesn't work well here} 11... a5 {[%cal Ra5a4]} 12. b3 {stopping a4 and preparing Na4} Nd7 13. Be2 Nc5 14. O-O Qb6 15. Nb5 Bd7 16. Rfd1 Bxb5 17. cxb5 Rfc8 18. f4 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3][%cal Ge4e5] Black does not have any counterplay. His position is worse.}) ({In case of} 11... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga8c8] White has a very interesting plan} 12. Be2 Rc8 13. b3 Qa5 {[#]} 14. Kf2 $5 {White is preparing for the endgame. therefore, he places his king closer to the center.} Rfd8 15. Rhd1 b5 16. Nd5 $5 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bd7 {The endgame has emerged. The White king's position on f2 is clearly better than on g1. White is starting to take over the space on the kingside.} 19. g4 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5]} bxc4 20. Bxc4 $14 {[%csl Ga6] White is a bit better}) 12. b3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gc3b5,Gc3a4] White strengthens the c4 pawn in advance and prepares the knight's jumps.} Rfc8 {is the main try} 13. g4 $5 {[%cal Yh2h5] a very clever move by GM Navara. On the one hand, this move creates the idea of attacking the kingside, but in fact, it prepares the aforementioned endgame but in a more advantageous version for White.} ({Now the main move is} 13. Be2 {then there are very similar endings, but due to the position of the e2 bishop, Black has a counterplay.} a6 {[%cal Yb7b5]} 14. Na4 $5 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga4b6] White is trying to exploit the weakness of the b6 square.} Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h5] The endgame has emerged.} Nd7 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rf7f5,Gd7c5] stopping Nb6} 16. g4 f5 $1 {It is a good moment for a counterplay} ({Black can't wait} 16... Rc6 17. h4 Rac8 18. h5 $14 {here White carried out his basic plan and Black has problems with counterplay. We will see this position later.}) 17. exf5 gxf5 18. h3 Rf8 19. f4 Rad8 $1 {[%cal Yd6d5] Now Black prepares a counterplay in the center.} 20. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5]} ({In the next game, Black finished his plan and equalized the position.} 20. Rhg1 d5 $1 21. gxf5 Bxf5 22. cxd5 Nf6 23. Nb6 Nxd5 24. Bc4 Be6 $11 {1-0 (37) Volokitin,A (2667)-Guseinov,G (2637) Chess.com INT 2024}) 20... d5 $1 21. cxd5 Nf6 22. Ke1 Nxd5 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 24. Rg1 $132 {The position is approximately equal.}) 13... a6 {[%cal Yb7b5] b5 is coming} ({After} 13... Qb4 {White goes to a better endgame} 14. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 15. exd5 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Bd7 17. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gh2h5]}) 14. Na4 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga4b6] The point of White'sWhite's strategy.} Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 {The endgame has emerged.[#]} Nd7 (15... Rab8 $6 {is worse} 16. Nb6 Rc6 17. Be2 Nd7 18. Nd5 $14 Bxd5 19. cxd5 Rcc8 20. b4 $14 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3][%cal Gh2h5] We discussed such endings in another chapter, White has an advantage.}) 16. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] White just continues his plan.} (16. Rg1 $6 {White can stop f5, but Black plays b5 with a good position.} Rcb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({In Navara's game was} 16... Rc6 17. Be2 $14 {White is a bit better. He won it. 1-0 (37) Navara,D (2707)-Jakovenko,D (2698) Jerusalem 2019.}) 17. Nc3 b5 $1 18. Nd5 (18. cxb5 axb5 $15 {[%cal Ga8a2,Gb5b4]}) 18... Bxd5 19. cxd5 Nc5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black is fine} 20. Bxc5 $6 {is bad} dxc5 21. Rxc5 $4 Bd4 $1 $19 {[%csl Rc5,Rg1]}) 16... Rc6 ({Now it is very important to understand what the difference is compared to 13.Вe2} 16... f5 $2 17. gxf5 gxf5 18. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gh3e6] a very unpleasant move for Black!} Rf8 $6 19. Rcg1 $1 {White wins by attacking the king directly} Kh8 {How to play now?[#]} 20. Rxg7 $1 Kxg7 21. Rg1+ $1 Kh8 (21... Kf7 22. exf5 $18 {[%csl Re6]}) 22. Bd4+ {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gd4h8]} Rf6 (22... Nf6 23. exf5 Bd7 24. Nb6 Rad8 25. Nd5 $18 {[%cal Gd4h8,Gd5e7] also bad}) 23. exf5 Bf7 24. Bxf6+ exf6 $16 {White won a pawn. Great attack in the endgame!}) ({Black doesn't solve all the problems in the following variant either} 16... Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 17. Nc3 b5 {force line} ({after} 17... a5 18. Be2 Kf8 19. h5 $14 {Black doesn't have b5 counterplay anymore.}) 18. cxb5 Ne5 (18... Bxc3+ 19. Rxc3 Rxc3 20. Kxc3 axb5 21. Be2 $14 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3] White is better off with two bishops and an extra pawn on the queenside}) 19. Be2 axb5 20. Nxb5 Nxf3+ 21. Bxf3 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rxb5 23. Rc7 $14 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3] Black needs to do something to counter the advance of the White pawns on the queenside.}) ({In case of} 16... Rcb8 {White can change his plan. He can grab a space on the queenside now.} 17. Nb6 $5 Nxb6 18. Bxb6 Rc8 {[#]} 19. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] killing Black's counterplay} Bb2 (19... Rc6 20. a5 $14) 20. Rc2 Ba3 21. a5 Bb4+ 22. Ke3 Bc5+ 23. Bxc5 Rxc5 24. b4 Rc6 25. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gh4h5] And White can strengthen on both sides. Black has a nasty position.}) 17. h5 $1 {a logical continuation. White is preparing a showdown on the kingside, Black no longer has a counterplay with f5.} ({In the next game, White played} 17. g5 Nc5 18. Nc3 Bxc3+ 19. Kxc3 {but after} b5 $1 {he made a mistake} 20. cxb5 $2 (20. Kb2 $14 {was still better for White}) 20... Nxe4+ 21. Kb4 Rxc1 22. Bxc1 Ng3 $132 {and Black got a great position. 1/2 (52) Michalik,P (2578)-Guseinov,G (2660) Batumi 2019}) 17... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black prepares b5.} ({If Black is waiting, then White is getting stronger, Black is having a bad play.} 17... Rac8 18. Be2 Bh8 19. Rhf1 b6 20. f4 $16 {[%csl Rd7,Re6][%cal Gf4f5] The Black pieces don't have enough space.}) ({Black can try} 17... Nc5 18. Nc3 Bxc3+ $5 19. Rxc3 b5 {[%csl Ge3,Gf1] Of course, he played b5, but now White has the advantage of two bishops} 20. Rc2 Rac8 21. hxg6 fxg6 (21... hxg6 $6 {is very dangerous} 22. Kc3 {[%cal Gc2h2]} bxc4 23. Rch2 $16) 22. Ke1 $14 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gc2h2] preparing Rh2 and attack on the kingside.}) 18. hxg6 {opening the king's flank for the rooks} fxg6 ({Worse try is} 18... hxg6 19. Nc3 Rc7 20. Be2 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh1h7,Gc3d5] White is a bit better.}) 19. Nc3 Bxc3+ ({After} 19... b5 20. Nd5 $1 Bxd5 21. exd5 Rcc8 22. f4 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Re7,Gf1][%cal Gf4f5] Black has many weaknesses}) 20. Rxc3 Rbc8 21. Bd4 $14 {[%csl Yd4,Yf1][%cal Gg4g5,Gf3f4] Then White starts the game on the kingside. He has two bishops and a better pawn structure. Conclusion: Using the example of this opening line, we looked at typical ideas that arise in the endgame of the Maroczy structure. The character of the game is in favor of White, it is not easy for Black to organize an active counterplay. White's main tasks are to control the center and strengthen the pawns of the kingside.} *

