{[%evp 0,53,38,-2,8,8,14,-19,-13,-30,18,13,23,23,23,12,28,22,28,31,31,30,34,40,69,61,48,50,39,44,42,24,44,48,58,61,80,104,81,82,82,71,73,80,58,74,74,74,81,81,77,73,78,81,81,81] In this chapter, we will look at the pawn structures that arise if White does not play Nd5 (such structures most often arise in the main variation of Maroczy after 10.Qd2). Here we will analyze the plans of White, arising after 10.Nb3, 10.Nc2 or 10.h3. White saves the knight from the exchange of Nc6-Nd4, which should be in Black's favor, since White has more space. White's plans: 1) to carry out f4 and play in the center or on the kingside (after e5 or f5); 2) to capture space on the queenside (after b4-a5-b5); 3) in case of Nd5, a transition to the considered structures is possible. Black's plans: 1) a6-b5 and opening of files on the queenside; 2) a5-a4 and siege of the c4 pawn with pieces; 3) exchange of pieces. These variations lead to very complex positions.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 g6 6. e4 d6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd7c6] This is the tabiya of the Maroczy variation. Black wants to trade knights and play Bc6. White tried many continuations.} 10. h3 {[%cal Gf2f4] White controls g4 square and prepares f4.} ({Another interesting try is} 10. Nb3 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] The knight escapes the exchange. White prepares to meet a5 with kd2. White also intends to carry out f4 with play in the center.} a5 $5 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5][%cal Ra5a4]} ({In case of slow play of Black} 10... Rc8 {White starts his active plan and gets an advantage} 11. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Be6 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd2e4]} Na5 13. b3 $14 {Black has problems with counterplay.} Ng4 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. Qxg4 Bxc3 16. Rac1 Bg7 17. f5 $16 {[%csl Rg8]}) ({In the next game, Black tried a leisurely setup} 10... b6 $5 11. f3 Ne8 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rac1 Ne5 14. Nd5 {White provokes e6 to make the d6 pawn weak.} e6 {[%csl Rd6]} 15. Nf4 Qe7 16. Rfd1 {now Black showed an interesting attempt at counterplay} f5 $5 17. exf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Rd6,Re6] an interesting structure emerged, Black had weak pawns in the center, but the pieces were given some freedom} 18. Nd4 Rf8 {1/2 (52) Polugaevsky,L (2630)-Ljubojevic,L (2610) Roquebrune 1992} 19. b3 $14 {[%csl Ya7,Yb6][%cal Ga2a5] in any case, after a4-a5 White is a bit better.}) 11. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd2e4,Gd2c4,Yc3a4,Ya4b6,Gf2f4,Yd2f3,Re4e5] The point of Nb3! Now White prevents a4 and prepares the transfer Na4-Nb6. At the same time, the knight is very usefully located on d2, because it protects c4 and e4, also after f4 White can transfer the knight to f3, where it will support e5.} (11. f3 $6 {gives time for} a4 $132 12. Nd2 $6 a3 $1 {[%cal Rg7a1]} 13. bxa3 Ng4 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Re3]}) 11... Be6 {Prepares Nd7} ({After} 11... Ne5 12. h3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Bc6 13. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf2f4,Ge4e5]} Ned7 14. Nb3 a4 15. Nd4 Qa5 16. Rab1 $14 {[%cal Yb2b4] White is better}) 12. f4 $5 {[%cal Gf4f5] With the bishop on e6, White is guided by the plan with f4-f5} Bd7 {[#] What plan should White implement now?} (12... Nd7 $4 {due to} 13. f5 $18 {[%csl Re6]}) (12... Bc8 13. Rc1 Nd7 14. Nf3 {[%cal Ye4e5,Yf4f5] White is ready to play in the center, and Black has no counterplay.}) 13. c5 $1 {a powerful breakthrough in the center} ({or} 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. c5 $5 {with the same idea}) 13... dxc5 14. e5 $1 Ne8 15. Bxc5 {with the open center, White has a much better position of the pieces.} Nc7 16. Nc4 Be6 {1/2 (32) Romanov,E (2624)-Chadaev,N (2573) Olginka 2011. Now after} 17. Bb6 $1 Qc8 18. Ne3 $16 {[%cal Ya1c1,Yc1c8] Black has a very dangerous position. Pay attention to the с5 idea!}) (10. Nc2 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gf2f4,Gc2a3,Ya7a5,Ya5a4,Ga3b5] This is a very interesting plan for White. White keeps more minor pieces on the board. His plan includes advancing f4 and playing in the center and on the kingside. After a5-a4, White often moves the knight Nc2-Na3, where it blocks the a4-pawn, protects the c4-pawn, and controls the weak b5-square. We will look at several typical games from this variation.} Be6 ({In the next game, White captured space on the queenside and then made a breakthrough there.} 10... Rc8 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qd2 Nd7 ({After} 12... Ng4 {White can trade his passive bishop} 13. Bxg4 Bxg4 14. Bh6 $5 {Now White prepares an attack on the kingside.} Qa5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ne3 $14 {[%cal Yf2f5] and after f4-f5 White can start his attack.}) 13. Rfd1 {[%cal Gb2b4] White finished his development. Now, he has started an improvement in the center and on the queenside.} Nc5 14. b4 $1 Nd7 15. Nd5 $16 Nce5 16. Nd4 Bxd5 17. cxd5 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7][%cal Ye3a7] After this exchange, the pawn structure is transformed,White is clearly better, Black's pawns on the queenside are very weak.} Nb6 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Rc1 Qb8 20. Nb5 Ned7 {How to play now?[#]} 21. a4 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7][%cal Ga4a5] a very strong plan.} a6 22. a5 $1 Na8 23. Na7 $5 {White prepares future sacrifice.} f5 24. exf5 gxf5 25. Nc6 $1 {decisive breakthrough} bxc6 {1-0 (41), Timofeev Artyom (RUS) 2690 - Mamedov Rauf (AZE) 2660 , Rijeka 17.3.2010 Ch Europe} 26. dxc6 Nf6 27. Bxa6 $18 {[%cal Yb4b5] White pawns are very strong, Black is lost. A good game on using the spatial advantage on the queenside.}) ({In the next, game White showed the correct reaction to Black's play on the queenside.} 10... a5 $5 {[%cal Ya5a4]} 11. Qd2 a4 12. f3 Qa5 13. Rfd1 Rfc8 {First, White placed his pieces in ideal positions, now he improves his knight.} 14. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rb5,Gc4][%cal Ya3c4,Ya4a3,Ya3b5] Here the knight is protecting the c4 pawn. In the future, White can move it to b5.} Be6 15. Nd5 {also ok for White} ({The computer prefers} 15. Rab1 Ne5 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 Nxd5 18. cxd5 Bd7 19. h3 $14 {[%cal Gf3f4] and f4 with better endgame.}) 15... Bxd5 {Georgiev Kiril (MKD) 2685 - Strikovic Aleksa (SRB) 2560 , Marrakesh 27.6.2010 It (open)} 16. cxd5 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 Nb4 18. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Ra4] In such an endgame, White has an advantage, since the a4 pawn can turn out to be a weakness.}) 11. f4 $5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf4f5] After the move Be6, playing f4-f5 is a typical reaction for White. By attacking the bishop, White often wins tempos for developing an attack on the Black king.} Qc8 (11... Nd7 $4 12. f5 $18 {[%csl Re6]}) ({Blacks cannot solve his problems by force} 11... Na5 12. b3 Ng4 13. Bxg4 Bxc3 14. f5 Bd7 15. Rc1 $14 {White prepares the initiative on the kingside}) 12. Qd2 Ng4 {Usually such an exchange is advantageous for White. In the game, Shirov immediately begins an attack on the king.} 13. Bxg4 Bxg4 14. f5 $5 {[%csl Yg4]} gxf5 15. Bh6 {An interesting sacrifice that worked well in the game.} (15. h3 $5 {was a bit better} f4 16. Bxf4 Be6 17. Ne3 $14 {[%csl Rg8] Black king can be in danger.}) 15... f4 $2 {Now Black is just worse.} (15... Bxh6 {was better} 16. Qxh6 fxe4 17. Rae1 $44 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Yc2e3,Yc3e4] This is a very complex position with compensation for White.}) 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rxf4 Kh8 18. Nd5 Be6 19. Nd4 Bxd5 20. exd5 Ne5 21. b3 Rg8 22. Raf1 $16 {[%csl Rh8] The Black king is very weak. White won it.} Rg4 23. Nf5 Rxf4 24. Qxf4 Qc7 25. Qg5 Ng6 26. Re1 f6 27. Qh6 e5 28. h4 Rg8 29. h5 Qc5+ 30. Re3 {1-0 (30) Shirov,A (2655)-Hausrath,D (2462) Germany 2024. It's a typical example of a White attack after f4-f5.}) (10. Qd2 {is the main line.}) 10... Nxd4 {Black continues his plan} ({After} 10... a6 $6 {White plays the same plan like in Nb3} 11. Nf3 $1 Rc8 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gd2c4,Rf2f4,Re4e5]} Be6 14. f4 Rfd8 15. a3 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2b4,Gf4f5]}) 11. Bxd4 $5 a5 (11... Bc6 12. Qc2 a5 {is the same position}) 12. Qc2 {[%cal Gf2f4] White prepares f4, so the queen goes here to protect the e4 pawn.} Bc6 ({After} 12... a4 13. b4 $1 axb3 14. axb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3b4] White is better}) 13. Rad1 Nd7 ({Recently Black tried} 13... a4 14. c5 {[%cal Yd1d8] White spoils the Black structure.} Re8 15. f3 Qa5 16. cxd6 exd6 17. a3 d5 $5 {Black counterattacks in the center.} 18. e5 Nh5 19. f4 Ng3 20. Rfe1 Nf5 {[%cal Gf7f6] The Black structure is worse, but he has improved the pieces significantly.} 21. Bf2 {In the following computer line, White proves his advantage} ({After} 21. Bf3 {Black got a counterplay} Nxd4 22. Rxd4 Qa7 23. Red1 f6 $1 $132 24. Kh1 fxe5 25. fxe5 Bxe5 26. Bxd5+ Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Qe3 28. R5d3 Qf4 29. g3 Qc4 30. Kh2 b5 {0-1 (53) Ladron de Guevara Pinto,P (2420)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2605) Linares 2021}) 21... d4 22. Ne4 Red8 23. Bc4 Rac8 24. b4 axb3 25. Bxb3 Qxa3 26. Qd3 $44 {[%cal Ge5e6,Gd3a3,Ge4g5]}) ({After a slow} 13... Qc7 {White changed the structure and won a good game} 14. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 15. exd5 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gh3h5]} Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qc3+ Kg8 18. Rd4 Nc5 19. Rfd1 a4 20. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5]} Qa5 21. Qc1 a3 22. b3 Rfe8 23. Bg4 {[%cal Yh4h5]} e5 24. dxe6 Nxe6 25. Rxd6 $18 {1-0 (33) Rakhmanov,A (2655)-Skoberne,J (2563) Batumi 2018}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d7,Gc4c5,Ge4e5,Yd1d8] White wants to exchange the passive bishop. Also, after the knight retreats, the center will be opened.} Ne5 {is the main} (15... Nf6 16. c5 Nxg4 17. hxg4 {the same position}) (15... Nc5 16. e5 $1 {[%cal Rd1d8]} f5 ({After} 16... Re8 17. b3 h5 18. Be2 Qc7 19. exd6 exd6 {[%csl Rd6]} 20. Nd5 $14 {White has a better pawn structure for free.}) 17. Be2 f4 {Black tries to get an active play} ({After} 17... Ne6 18. Rfe1 Qc7 19. exd6 exd6 20. Nd5 $18 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 {White'sWhite's positional advantage is too big} Nf4 22. Qc3+ Rf6 23. Rb5 Re8 24. Bf1 Rxe1 25. Qxe1 b6 26. Qe3 {1-0 (48) Andreikin,D (2732)-Jones,G (2645) Reykjavik 2016}) 18. Rfe1 f3 19. Bxf3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Rxf3 21. Kg2 Rf5 22. Qd2 Kg8 23. Nd5 Ne6 24. exd6 Qxd6 25. Qe3 $16 {but nevertheless White has a big advantage due to control in the center}) (15... f5 $6 {is bad} 16. exf5 h5 17. Be2 Rxf5 18. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Yg6,Rg7,Yh5] Black king is too weak}) 16. c5 $1 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Nxg4 17. hxg4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2,Gg2,Gg4] A very unusual pawn structure has emerged, Black will soon have a weak pawn on d6, White has a big space advantage.} Qc8 (17... b5 18. cxd6 exd6 19. f3 $16 {[%csl Rd6] Black will lose d6 pawn soon}) (17... Bd7 {is worse} 18. cxd6 (18. g5 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] wins slowly}) 18... Bxg4 19. dxe7 Qxe7 20. Nd5 Qe5 21. f3 Rac8 22. Qf2 $16 {White is better 1-0 (37) Grandelius,N (2655)-Thybo,J (2465) Vaxjo 2017.}) 18. cxd6 Qxg4 (18... exd6 {is even worse} 19. f3 Qe6 20. Rd4 Rfd8 21. Rfd1 Qe5 22. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rd6] In the game, White quickly exploited the weakness on d6. 1-0 (40) Shimanov,A (2587)-Shaposhnikov,E (2568) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019}) 19. dxe7 Rfe8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Qc3+ $1 {is stronger. White avoids the next line.} ({After} 21. exd5 Rac8 22. Qd2 Rxe7 23. Qxa5 Rc2 {Black has some counterplay} 24. d6 Rxf2 $1 25. Qd5 Rxf1+ 26. Rxf1 Rd7 $16 {White is better}) 21... Kg8 22. exd5 Rxe7 23. d6 Rd7 {A very unpleasant endgame for Black has arisen. He is forced to play difficult defense. Unsurprisingly, Black has stopped going for this variation.} 24. Rd5 Qb4 25. Qe5 a4 26. a3 Qb6 27. Re1 $16 {and White won it. 1-0 (43) Cheparinov,I (2711)-Amin,B (2709) Zagreb 2018 Conclusion: We have looked at the side plans for White in the main Maroczy variation. White is always aiming for an advantage. It is very difficult for Black to show counterplay. This may be why Black has recently chosen less popular plans (see, for example, the plan with Qb6).} *

